<font color="#FF0000">MORE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Apr 25 20:56:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
More,  I've calmed down. A little bit.  Very little.  But, this entire site has been about healing and caring.  These last months have made able to articulate feelings that have been dormant for a long time. <br>
To have those feelings of comeraderie and brotherhood shaken to the core was hard to take.<br>
I again state that the Vietnamese people are not the cause for us being where we are today.  They are easy targets. BUT THEY ARE NOT THE CAUSE!!  Everybody get that?  I say again, they are not the cause.<br>
If you ain't figured it out yet.  You need to look a little deeper into yourself. As Dr. Spatz did. As a number of us have.<br>
For God's sake, if we can't talk to each other about these things I guess it is time to get my butt back into counseling.  Each of us react to these things differently.  I am removed from a lot of the Vietnamese population here in Northern Virginia.  But when I was in turmoil, I lived only 5 miles from the largest concentration of Vietnamese in the U.S. today.  It was bitterness and envy to see them doing so well.  To be incorporated into a life that I was still on the outside of.  My response was not to go there or talk to any Vietnamese.  Until I had to. <br>
The horror stories that I heard when I finally listened made me feel ashamed.  The loss that this people have suffered is incredible!<br>
I am not advocating that we all join hands and give three cheers for the Vietnamese.  But for Christs sake, Maintain a little common sense!<br>
We who chose to put our e-mail addresses on our posts sometimes invite attacks off line.  But I am willing to deal with those consquences.  I will talk to anyone that wants to debate civilly and without ad hominum attacks.  Even if then you want to &quot;get down&quot;, we can play there, too. Oops, there I go again. 
